data.name: Label1.Text
data.value:
Sagittarius is at the center of the Milky Way Galaxy, which is at its densest point as it makes its way through the constellation. The constellation’s brightest stars form a star pattern, and they all come together to form the archer’s bow. Within Sagittarius lies a bright radio source known as Sagittarius A* (pronounced “Sagittarius A-star”), a supermassive black hole in the heart of the galaxy. While we can’t observe the black hole directly, we can observe how it affects the stars around it.
In Greek mythology, Sagittarius is usually identified as a centaur: half human, half horse. It’s largely debated what centaur the constellation represents, but many believe that it’s Chiron, the son of the Titan Cronos. Chiron was different from other centaurs; he was wise, having tutored many great heroes such as Hercules and Jason. One day, Chiron was accidentally shot with a poisoned arrow by Hercules. Even though he was a great physician, he couldn’t heal himself. Being immortal, Chiron couldn’t die but was pained by the poisoned arrow. Forced to give up his immortality in order to escape his torment, Zeus saw fit to immortalize him in the stars instead.
